<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="369">Range Reported by John T. Longino (1997) from the Atlantic slope of Costa Rica to 1100 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="369">
Biology According to Longino (1997), 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181837" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole amabilis Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole amabilis Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amabilis">amabilis</taxonomicName>
occurs in wet forest. Nests have been found in Cecropia sapling internodes, in foliar pouches of a myrmecophytic melastome, and in a dead stick in leaf litter. The colony in the dead stick was separated from a colony of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33994" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole scrobifera Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole scrobifera Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scrobifera">Pheidole scrobifera</taxonomicName>
by a plug of woody frass; fighting between the two species ensued when the plug was removed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
